<br>
I don't mind if someone shows up and says 'hey, you're not at zone in, mind if we pull roamers for xp?'.  Sure, no problem.  Have fun.  But it's pretty obvious that your average raid is in Hate for the drops.  When you start taking the drops (at least without clearing it with the raid leader of the raid in progress), you're hosing other people who came to Hate in the hopes of improving their gear some.  <br>
<br>
Everyone wants the good loot.  It's understandable and even necessary with the way the game is built.  But how hard is it to take a step back for a moment and think 'how would I feel if I was on a raid and my clerics had been here patiently waiting for four or more hours only to find out that someone had cleared the mobs while we were doing other mobs'?<br>
<br>
Dunno.  Maybe it's just me. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><center><img src=http://www.idiom.com/~mony/gifs/kyenasig3.jpg><br>Bard of the 49th Song<br>Ancient Prophecy<br>Mithaniel Marr</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEEFDE><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub18.ezboard.com/ulillywhite.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lillywhite</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>MithMarr Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#006400>(9/6/01 9:50:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub18.ezboard.com/fmithanielmarrdailynewsfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=772.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Jumping Planes Raids</span><hr size=1> Hi!  No Mony it is not just you.  Two raids simply can not make either of the groups happy since people both raid groups will find that all their mobs for thier item drops have been pulled by the other raid.  I have seen this happen at least 3 times I was in hate, where the revenants were all pulled by another guild &quot;sharing&quot; the zone.  Well, it really is not &quot;sharing&quot;.  One can no help the feeling when one's guild is there first, that the second guild coming along to &quot;share&quot; the zone is &quot;stealing&quot; the drop items that your guild would have gotten if not for thier presence. The &quot;PNP&quot; in an idealistic system, but like most ideal systems, it fails miserably when confronted by human feelings and practical reality.  Ideal systems are normally not natural, and often they go against human nature, which is terratorial in nature.  <br>
<br>
To ease friction, the guilds on mith mar should sit down and discuss rules that they will enforce among themselves, how to handle these situations.  For example, I know that many people won't post their ITR on this Board, since some guilds then use that info to get there 2 hrs before the ITR post time and &quot;claim jump&quot; the area.  That means you can't plan raids and have everyone plan their RL lives around the planned raid.  In practice, this ideal system does not work because of the few who won't follow it, and enforcement would require coordinated effort by many guilds.  Or it might be that we should agree to all follow a 1st come, 1st serve policy, and that the second guild on the scene will leave.  The problems and conflict arise because the guilds are using 3 different systems: PNP, ITR, and 1c1s.  If we could all agree to one system,  I believe the problems would diminish. <br>
<br>
Lillywhite <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFF8DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub18.ezboard.com/ubeautia.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Beautia</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>MithMarr Squire<br><img src=http://www.winterblood.com/mmdn/star2.gif></span><br>  Posts: 49<br> <font color=#006400>(9/6/01 9:57:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub18.ezboard.com/fmithanielmarrdailynewsfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=772.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Jumping Planes Raids</span><hr size=1> I actually think the key word here is 'compromise'. Sure - it's not as good as getting all the candy yourself, but it does seem the polite way to deal with things, and maybe all win in the long run.<br>
<br>
Sometimes, sure, there's just no outright sharing. But i think the most important thing is to talk to one another and be reasonable. Even if your group is the group that gets turned away. Don't you find that people tend to be much more apt to help one another or work something out if everyone is a bit giving in the situation? Sometimes even backing down on what they stated that simply HAD to have out of the raid/encounter.<br>
<br>
Beautia <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEEFDE><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub18.ezboard.com/ulillywhite.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lillywhite</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>MithMarr Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#006400>(9/7/01 7:24:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub18.ezboard.com/fmithanielmarrdailynewsfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=772.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Jumping Planes Raids</span><hr size=1> Hi Beautia!  Yes, depending on the situation, compromise and accomodation will work.  It would be hard to compromise on some camps, that have very long pop times.  In general, it really matters little what the rules are, just so long as everyone has the same ones.  Conflict results when one group says one set of rules they are following is fair, while the other group says no, that is wrong, they don't follow those principles.  In RL, governments are set up to impose rules and try to avoid these problems. The same things happen in game, but the only real government is VI, trying to make a ideal rules for less than ideal conflicts.  It would be possible, to form a United Guilds of Norrath in which common rules would be agreed upon, and to establish a &quot;world court&quot;  in which guilds could bring grievances, for binding judgment by players elected for that purpose.  As you can see, &quot;fairness&quot; and &quot;justice&quot; would be hard work.  Typically, it is often more expedient in the game to walk away from any conflicts,  just forgive any injustices and realize it is &quot;only a game&quot; and move on to something else.<br>
<br>
Lillywhite <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFF8DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub18.ezboard.com/ukorrellian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Korrellian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>MithMarr Knight<br><img src=http://www.winterblood.com/mmdn/star2.gif><img src=http://www.winterblood.com/mmdn/star2.gif><img src=http://www.winterblood.com/mmdn/star2.gif></span><br>  Posts: 192<br> <font color=#006400>(9/7/01 9:58:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub18.ezboard.com/fmithanielmarrdailynewsfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=772.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Jumping Planes Raids</span><hr size=1> It really works out great if a compromise can be found, which has been the case for us a few times.  Usually there will be another 'raid' interested in something specific, one related to epic's and another just to farm armor.  These 2 types can usually coexist pretty well, if like mentioned above they are good.  We've done it a few times, mostly with Japenese who always show every courtesy and we in return let them loot any armors we dont need.<br>
